<subSubSection id="58DB8BE5FFD9FFF5FF66FEA2A1142FB8" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="107ED86EFFD9FFF5FF66FEA2A1142FB8" blockId="51.[151,638,194,1092]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF66FEA2A1772F22" bold="true" box="[175,290,327,348]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF30FE87A1122F09" box="[249,327,354,375]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">riparius</emphasis>
, meaning of or belonging near the bank of a river. So named because each specimen of the 
<typeStatus id="CF7A66CCFFD9FFF5FEC5FE72A1602FD2" box="[268,309,407,428]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">type</typeStatus>
series was collected near a river in 
<collectingCountry id="68D698FEFFD9FFF5FF7BFE54A0BE2FB8" box="[178,235,433,454]" name="Brazil" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Brazil</collectingCountry>
or 
<collectingCountry id="68D698FEFFD9FFF5FEC6FE54A1682FB8" box="[271,317,433,454]" name="Peru" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Peru</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58DB8BE5FFD9FFF5FF66FE29A1B52CFE" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="107ED86EFFD9FFF5FF66FE29A23A2C35" blockId="51.[151,638,194,1092]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF66FE29A1782F9F" bold="true" box="[175,301,460,481]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FEF3FE29A1B92F9F" box="[314,492,460,481]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FEF3FE29A1B92F9F" box="[314,492,460,481]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga riparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from 
<collectingCountry id="68D698FEFFD9FFF5FF5EFE03A0932F85" box="[151,198,486,507]" name="Peru" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Peru</collectingCountry>
, with 
<specimenCount id="06C713E7FFD9FFF5FECEFE03A1DB2F85" box="[263,398,486,507]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingCountry id="68D698FEFFD9FFF5FE19FE03A25E2F85" box="[464,523,486,507]" name="Brazil" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="88FAC4EBFFD9FFF5FDD2FE03A2262F85" box="[539,627,486,507]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="50.[197,237,1570,1589]" captionTargetBox="[176,1191,194,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-1@50.[172,1194,191,1552]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figs. 109–114. Hoplopyga riparia. 109–110) Habitus of allotype female; 111) Mesometasternal process, ventral view; 112–113) Parameres; 114) Distribution." pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Fig. 114</figureCitation>
). This species is represented by only 
<specimenCount id="06C713E7FFD9FFF5FE23FDE4A22F2C68" box="[490,634,513,534]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" type="generic">five specimens</specimenCount>
, and additional collecting or museum specimens will better define the distribution of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="107ED86EFFD9FFF5FF66FDB4A1B52CFE" blockId="51.[151,638,194,1092]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF66FDB4A1CC2C18" bold="true" box="[175,409,593,614]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Temporal Distribution.</emphasis>
February (1), May (1), June (1), August (1), October (1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58DB8BE5FFD9FFF5FF66FD63A1712A3A" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="107ED86EFFD9FFF5FF66FD63A1CF2A71" blockId="51.[151,638,194,1092]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF66FD63A1492CE5" bold="true" box="[175,284,646,667]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FEE3FD63A1BA2CE5" box="[298,495,646,667]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FEE3FD63A1BA2CE5" box="[298,495,646,667]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga riparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FF36FD45A1332CCB" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[255,358,672,693]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liturata">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF36FD45A1332CCB" box="[255,358,672,693]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">H. liturata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished by having punctures that continue to the base of the elytra near the scutellum. In 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FE03FD33A26C2C95" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[458,569,726,747]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liturata">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FE03FD33A26C2C95" box="[458,569,726,747]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">H. liturata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, these punctures do not reach the base of the elytra near the scutellum. 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FEF9FCEEA1BA2D5E" box="[304,495,779,800]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FEF9FCEEA1BA2D5E" box="[304,495,779,800]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga riparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also larger (
<quantity id="D739758BFFD9FFF5FF56FCC0A1632D44" box="[159,310,805,827]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.66" metricValueMax="1.76" metricValueMin="1.56" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" unit="mm" value="16.6" valueMax="17.6" valueMin="15.6">15.6–17.6 mm</quantity>
) than typical 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FE03FCC0A26D2D44" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[458,568,805,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liturata">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FE03FCC0A26D2D44" box="[458,568,805,826]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">H. liturata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens and has a mesometasternal process that widens just before the apex. 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FE77FCBEA2282D0E" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[446,637,859,880]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liturata">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FE77FCBEA2282D0E" box="[446,637,859,880]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga liturata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually smaller than 
<quantity id="D739758BFFD9FFF5FE4CFC90A1B72DF4" box="[389,482,885,906]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.58" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" unit="mm" value="15.8">15.8 mm</quantity>
, and the mesometasternal process never widens just before the apex. 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FF11FC4FA1C82DC1" box="[216,413,938,959]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF11FC4FA1C82DC1" box="[216,413,938,959]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga riparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName id="D7C1A3EDFFD9FFF5FE85FC20A1AF2DA7" authority="species" authorityName="SPECIES" box="[332,506,964,986]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FE85FC20A1E72DA4" box="[332,434,965,986]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Hoplopyga</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by its mottled dorsal appearance and the distinct form of the male parameres (
<figureCitation id="88FAC4EBFFD9FFF5FECCFC1FA1DB2A71" box="[261,398,1017,1039]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="50.[197,237,1570,1589]" captionTargetBox="[176,1191,194,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-1@50.[172,1194,191,1552]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figs. 109–114. Hoplopyga riparia. 109–110) Habitus of allotype female; 111) Mesometasternal process, ventral view; 112–113) Parameres; 114) Distribution." pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Figs. 112–113</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="107ED86EFFD9FFF5FF66FBF1A1712A3A" blockId="51.[151,638,194,1092]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">
<emphasis id="22B5047CFFD9FFF5FF66FBF1A11B2A57" bold="true" box="[175,334,1044,1065]" pageId="51" pageNumber="630">Natural History.</emphasis>
Nothing is known of the biology of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
